snippet.textDisplay:
Many 5G applications require end-to-end multiple point/user connections that achieve low latency in addition to adequate bandwidth. This means 5G will take time to ramp to the performance level that it makes a market difference. Think about what the bulk of '5G Apps' are: IoT/Machine-to-machine, real-time gaming, conferencing, video sharing, social media apps, 5G assisted and autonomous vehicle-to-vehicle apps all require that a critical mass of adoption occur before enough users and things will have 5G to make the end-to-end communications '5G' rather than limited by the weakest link 3G, 4G or wired connections.


4G was primarily about individual end user applications including YouTube, Netflix OTT media, Facebook, Twitter,  WhatsApp, Instagram, WeChat. Many of these and new social media apps are pursuing real-time services. The crossing point between network capabilities and the apps in the hands of the multiple users will into 2022-2023 time frame. Until then, we are all talking about the old paradigm that focuses on individual user bandwidth... which is late and lame to the party.
